During the [2008 South Ossetia war](/2008_South_Ossetia_war), air power confronted formidable SAM systems, such as the 1980s [Buk-M1](/Buk-M1).

In February 2018, an Israeli F-16 fighter was downed in the [Golan Heights](/Golan_Heights) province after attacking an Iranian target in Syria. [^71^] [^72^] [^73^] [^74^] In 2006, Israel also lost a helicopter over Lebanon, shot down by a Hezbollah rocket. [^75^]

### AA Warfare Systems

A [Gepard](/Flakpanzer_Gepard) in motion at the 2015 Military Day in [Uffenheim](/Uffenheim). The Gepard is an autonomous all-weather-capable German [self-propelled anti-aircraft gun](/Self-propelled_anti-aircraft_gun) system armed with twin [Oerlikon GDF](/Oerlikon_GDF).
[Bangladesh Army](/Bangladesh_Army) CS/AA3 35 mm twin anti-aircraft gun system along with its FW-2 [fire control radar](/Fire_control_radar) system behind. CS/AA3 is a Chinese variant of the Oerlikon GDF.

While infantry firearms, particularly machine guns, can be employed against low-altitude air targets, often with notable success, their effectiveness is generally limited, and muzzle flashes betray infantry positions. The speed and altitude of modern jet aircraft restrict engagement opportunities, and critical systems may be armoured on aircraft designed for the [ground attack role](/Ground-attack_aircraft). Adaptations of standard [autocannons](/Autocannon), originally intended for air-to-ground use, and heavier [artillery](/Artillery) systems were commonly used for most anti-aircraft gunnery. This began with standard pieces on new mountings and evolved into specially designed guns with significantly higher performance prior to World War II.

The [shells](/Shell_(projectile)) fired by these weapons are typically fitted with various types of [fuses](/Fuse_(explosives)) ([barometric](/Barometric_pressure), time-delay, or [proximity](/Proximity_fuse)) to detonate near the airborne target, dispersing a shower of high-velocity metal fragments. For shorter-range engagements, a lighter weapon with a higher [rate of fire](/Rate_of_fire) is required to increase the probability of a hit on a fast airborne target. Weapons ranging from 20 mm to 40 mm calibre have been widely employed in this capacity. Smaller weapons, typically .50 caliber or even 8 mm rifle-caliber guns, have been used in the smallest mounts.

Unlike heavier guns, these smaller weapons see widespread use due to their lower cost and ability to track targets rapidly. Classic examples of autocannons and large-caliber guns include the [40 mm autocannon from Bofors](/Bofors_40_mm_L/60_gun) and the [8.8 cm FlaK 18, 36 gun](/8.8_cm_Flak_18/36/37/41) designed by Krupp. Artillery weapons of this nature have largely been superseded by effective surface-to-air missile systems introduced in the 1950s, although many nations retained them. The development of surface-to-air missiles began in [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany) during the latter stages of World War II with missiles such as the [Wasserfall](/Wasserfall), though no operational system was deployed before the war's end. These represented new attempts to enhance the effectiveness of [anti-aircraft systems](/Anti-aircraft) in the face of the growing threat from [bombers](/Bomber). Land-based SAMs can be deployed from fixed installations or mobile launchers, either wheeled or tracked. The tracked vehicles are typically armoured, purpose-built platforms for carrying SAMs.

Larger SAMs may be deployed in fixed launchers but can be towed and redeployed as needed. SAMs launched by individuals are known in the United States as Man-Portable Air Defence Systems (MANPADS). Former Soviet Union MANPADS have been exported worldwide and are utilized by numerous armed forces. Targets for non-MANPAD SAMs are usually acquired by air-search [radar](/Radar), tracked, and then "locked-on" before the SAM is fired. Potential targets, if they are military aircraft, will be [identified as friend or foe](/Identification_Friend_or_Foe) before engagement. Advances in the latest, relatively inexpensive short-range missiles have begun to replace autocannons in this role.

Soviet [85mm](/85_mm_air_defense_gun_M1939_(52-K)) anti-aircraft guns deployed in the vicinity of [St Isaac's Cathedral](/Saint_Isaac%27s_Cathedral) during the [Siege of Leningrad](/Siege_of_Leningrad) (formerly Petrograd, now St. Petersburg) in 1941.

The interceptor aircraft, or simply interceptor, is a type of [fighter aircraft](/Fighter_aircraft) specifically designed to intercept and destroy enemy aircraft, particularly [bombers](/Bomber_aircraft). These typically rely on high speed and altitude capabilities. A number of jet interceptors, such as the [F-102 Delta Dagger](/F-102_Delta_Dagger), the [F-106 Delta Dart](/F-106_Delta_Dart), and the [MiG-25](/Mikoyan-Gurevich_MiG-25), were developed in the period following World War II up to the late 1960s. Their importance diminished as the role of [strategic bombing](/Strategic_bombing) shifted towards [ICBMs](/ICBM). This type of aircraft is invariably distinguished from other fighter designs by superior speeds, shorter operating ranges, and significantly reduced ordnance payloads.

[Radar](/Radar) systems utilize [electromagnetic](/Electromagnetic_radiation) waves to determine the range, altitude, direction, or speed of aircraft and [weather formations](/Weather_forecasting). They provide tactical and operational warning and direction, primarily during defensive operations. In their functional roles, they support combat operations through target search, threat detection, [guidance](/Missile_guidance), [reconnaissance](/Reconnaissance), [navigation](/Radar_navigation), [instrumentation], and [weather reporting](/Weather_radar).

### Anti-UAV Defences

See also: [Unmanned aerial vehicle § Counter unmanned air system](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle)

An anti-UAV defence system (AUDS) is designed for defence against military [unmanned aerial vehicles](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle). A variety of designs have been developed, employing technologies such as lasers, [^76^] net-guns and air-to-air netting, signal jamming, and in-flight hacking for signal hijacking. [^77^] Anti-UAV defence systems have been deployed against [ISIL](/Islamic_State_of_Iraq_and_the_Levant) drones during the [Battle of Mosul (2016–2017)](/Battle_of_Mosul_(2016%E2%80%932017)). [^78^] [^79^]

Alternative approaches for countering UAVs have included using shotguns at close range and, for smaller drones, training eagles to intercept them in flight. [^77^] This method is primarily effective against relatively small UAVs and [loitering munitions](/Loitering_munition) (also referred to as "suicide drones"). Larger UCAVs, such as the [MQ-1 Predator](/MQ-1_Predator), can be (and frequently are) shot down using methods similar to those employed against manned aircraft of comparable size and flight profiles. [^80^] [^81^]

The [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy)'s [Type 45 destroyers](/Type_45_destroyer) are advanced air defence platforms.

### Future Developments

#### Guns

Guns are increasingly being relegated to specialized roles, such as the Dutch [Goalkeeper CIWS](/Goalkeeper_CIWS). This system employs the [GAU-8 Avenger](/GAU-8_Avenger) 30 mm seven-barrel [Gatling gun](/Gatling_gun) for last-ditch anti-missile and anti-aircraft defence. However, even this formerly frontline weapon is currently being supplanted by newer missile systems, like the [RIM-116 Rolling Airframe Missile](/RIM-116_Rolling_Airframe_Missile), which is smaller, faster, and allows for mid-flight course correction (guidance) to ensure a hit. To bridge the gap between guns and missiles, Russia, in particular, produces the [Kashtan CIWS]. This system integrates both guns and missiles for final defence, featuring two six-barrel 30 mm [Gsh-6-30](/Gryazev-Shipunov_GSh-6-30) rotary cannons and eight [9M311](/9M311) surface-to-air missiles for its defensive capabilities.

The future of projectile-based weaponry may lie in the [railgun](/Railgun). Currently, tests are underway to develop systems capable of inflicting damage comparable to a [Tomahawk](/Tomahawk_(missile_family)) missile, but at a fraction of the cost. In February 2008, the [US Navy](/US_Navy) conducted a railgun test, firing a shell at 5,600 miles per hour (9,000 km/h) using 10 megajoules of energy. Its projected performance includes a muzzle velocity exceeding 13,000 miles per hour (21,000 km/h), with accuracy sufficient to hit a 5-meter target from 200 nautical miles (370 km) away, firing at a rate of 10 shots per minute. It is anticipated to be ready between 2020 and 2025. [^82^] While these systems are currently designed for static targets, adapting them for retargeting capabilities would position them as the next generation of AA systems.

#### Counter-Stealth

See also: [Stealth aircraft § Countermeasures](/Stealth_aircraft)

A significant challenge to the all-missile approach is the current proliferation of [stealth aircraft](/Stealth_aircraft). Long-range missiles depend on long-range detection to provide adequate lead time for engagement. Stealth designs drastically reduce detection ranges, often rendering the aircraft virtually unseen until it is too late for interception. Developing systems for the detection and tracking of stealthy aircraft poses a major obstacle for anti-aircraft advancements.

However, as [stealth technology](/Stealth_technology) evolves, so too does anti-stealth technology. Multiple transmitter radars, such as [bistatic radars](/Bistatic_radar) and [low-frequency radars](/Low-frequency_radar), are reported to possess the capability to detect stealth aircraft. Advanced thermographic cameras, particularly those incorporating [QWIPs](/Quantum_well_infrared_photodetector), could optically identify stealth aircraft irrespective of their [radar cross-section](/Radar_cross-section) (RCS). Furthermore, side-looking radars, high-powered [optical](/Optical) [satellites](/Satellite), and sky-scanning, high-[aperture](/Aperture), high-sensitivity [radars](/Radar) like [radio telescopes](/Radio_telescope), would all be capable of narrowing down the location of a stealth aircraft under specific parameters. [^83^] The newest SAMs claim the ability to detect and engage stealth targets, with the Russian [S-400](/S-400_(SAM)) being particularly notable. It is claimed to detect a target with a 0.05-square-meter RCS from 90 km away. [^84^]

#### Laser

Another potential weapon system for anti-aircraft applications is the [laser](/Laser). Although air planners have envisioned lasers in combat since the late 1960s, only the most modern laser systems are currently approaching what could be considered "experimental usefulness." Specifically, the [Tactical High Energy Laser] can be employed in anti-aircraft and anti-missile roles. The [ALKA](/ALKA_(weapon)) [directed-energy weapon](/Directed-energy_weapon) (DEW) system, a Turkish dual electromagnetic/laser weapon developed by [Roketsan](/Roketsan), allegedly destroyed one of [GNC's](/General_National_Congress) [Wing Loong II](/Wing_Loong_II) [UAVs](/Unmanned_Aerial_Vehicle). If accurate, this would represent the first documented instance of a vehicle-mounted combat laser successfully destroying another combat vehicle during actual wartime conditions. [^85^]

### Force Structures

See also: [Air defence forces](/Defence_Forces)

Most Western and Commonwealth militaries integrate air defence strictly within the traditional branches of the military (i.e., army, navy, and air force), either as a [separate arm](/Military_branch) or as a component of artillery units. In the [British Army](/British_Army), for example, air defence falls under the artillery arm. Conversely, in the [Pakistan Army](/Pakistan_Army), it was separated from the artillery in 1990 to form its own distinct arm. This contrasts with some countries, largely communist or former communist nations, where not only are there provisions for air defence within the army, navy, and air force, but specific branches exist solely dedicated to the air defence of national territory. An example is the Soviet [PVO Strany](/Soviet_Air_Defence_Forces). The [USSR](/USSR) also maintained a separate strategic rocket force responsible for [nuclear](/Thermonuclear_weapon) [intercontinental ballistic missiles](/Intercontinental_ballistic_missile).

#### Navy

Soviet/Russian [AK-630](/AK-630) [CIWS (close-in weapon system)](/Close-in_weapon_system).
Model of the multirole [IDAS missile](/IDAS_(missile)) of the [German Navy](/German_Navy), which can be fired from submerged anti-aircraft weapon systems.

Smaller boats and ships typically mount machine guns or rapid-fire cannons, which can often prove lethal to low-flying aircraft when linked to a [radar](/Radar)-directed [fire-control system](/Fire-control_system). Some vessels, such as [Aegis](/Aegis_combat_system)-equipped destroyers and cruisers, pose as significant a threat to aircraft as any land-based air defence system. Generally, naval vessels command respect from aircraft, and the reverse is equally true. [Carrier battle groups](/Carrier_battle_group) are exceptionally well defended, not only comprising numerous vessels with formidable air defence armament but also possessing the capability to launch [fighter jets](/Fighter_jet) for [combat air patrol](/Combat_air_patrol) overhead to intercept incoming airborne threats.

Nations like Japan utilize their SAM-equipped vessels to establish an outer air defence perimeter and act as [radar pickets](/Radar_picket) in the defence of their Home Islands. Similarly, the United States employs its Aegis-equipped ships as integral components of its [Aegis Ballistic Missile Defense System](/Aegis_Ballistic_Missile_Defense_System) for the defence of the Continental United States.

Certain modern submarines, such as the [Type 212 submarines](/Type_212_submarine) of the [German Navy](/German_Navy), are equipped with surface-to-air missile systems, recognizing helicopters and [anti-submarine warfare](/Anti-submarine_warfare) aircraft as significant threats. The concept of subsurface-launched anti-air missiles was first proposed by US Navy Rear Admiral Charles B. Momsen in a 1953 article. [^86^]

#### Layered Air Defence

A [RIM-67](/RIM-67_Standard) surface-to-air missile intercepts a [Firebee](/Firebee) drone at [White Sands](/White_Sands,_New_Mexico), 1980.

Layered air defence in naval tactics, particularly within a carrier group, is often structured around a system of concentric layers with the aircraft carrier at its core. The outermost layer is typically provided by the carrier's own aircraft, specifically its [AEW&C](/Airborne_early_warning_and_control) aircraft operating in conjunction with Combat Air Patrols (CAP). Should an attacker penetrate this layer, subsequent layers would consist of [surface-to-air missiles](/Surface-to-air_missile) carried by the carrier's escorts. These include area-defence missiles, such as the [RIM-67 Standard](/RIM-67_Standard), with a range of up to 100 nmi, and point-defence missiles, like the [RIM-162 ESSM](/RIM-162_ESSM), with a range up to 30 nmi. Finally, virtually every modern warship is equipped with small-caliber guns, including a [CIWS](/Close-in_weapon_system), which is typically a radar-controlled [Gatling gun](/Gatling_gun) of 20 mm to 30 mm calibre, capable of firing several thousand rounds per minute. [^87^]

#### Army

